crowdsourced_ids_results.rule_msg: ET INFO Observed Google DNS over HTTPS Domain (dns .google in TLS SNI)
crowdsourced_ids_results.rule_raw: alert tls $HOME_NET any -> $EXTERNAL_NET any (msg:"ET INFO Observed Google DNS over HTTPS Domain (dns .google in TLS SNI)"; flow:established,to_server; threshold: type both, track by_src, count 1, seconds 600; tls.sni; dotprefix; content:".dns.google"; endswith; reference:url,developers.google.com/speed/public-dns/docs/doh/; classtype:misc-activity; sid:2047866; rev:4; metadata:affected_product Any, attack_target Client_Endpoint, created_at 2022_02_07, deployment Perimeter, performance_impact Low, confidence High, signature_severity Informational, tag DoH, updated_at 2023_10_05, reviewed_at 2023_10_05, former_sid 2851058; target:src_ip;)

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis:
The PDF file is assessed as a legitimate business document with no malicious intent. The internal technical analysis found no evidence of an execution chain, embedded scripts, or automatic actions. While the file exhibits significant structural problems, such as numerous decoding errors across its streams, these anomalies are not accompanied by any malicious triggers or payloads and are considered indicative of a corrupted file rather than a threat.

This conclusion is strongly supported by the visual analysis, which identifies the document as a professionally formatted business invitation from a Russian company, LLC "Contract Center". The content, targeting professionals in the Russian defense industry, is coherent and specific. The branding, contact information, and domain name (`contract-center.com`) are all consistent with the purported sender. The document lacks any red flags typical of phishing, such as urgency cues, grammatical errors, or suspicious requests. Taken together, the evidence indicates the file is a benign, albeit structurally flawed, business communication.
